dark.text is a library for working with text (strings).

  `Na`(`Vx`):       `Nargument` format for `Vx`, as a string
  `Nb`(`Vx`):       decodes `Nbase64` text `Vx` as an array of bytes
  `Nc`:          (not yet used)
  `Nd`(`Vx`, `Vy`):    `Ndecorrupts` `Vx`, only matching for `Vy` if given (*)
  `Ne`:          (not yet used)
  `Nf`(`Vx`, `Vy`):    `Nfinds` matches of `Vy` in `Vx`
  `Ng`(`Vx`, `Vy`):    unique `Ngroups` from matches of `Vy` in `Vx`
  `Nh`:          (not yet used)
  `Ni`(`Vx`):       checks if `Vx` `Nis` text
  `Nj`(`Vx`):       converts to `VJSON` string
  `Nk`(`Vx`, `Vy`, `Vz`): makes `Ncut` of `Vx` starting at `Vy`, ending just after `Vz` or at end of `Vx`
  `Nl`(`Vx`):       `Nlowercases` `Vx`
  `Nm`(`Vx`, `Vy`):    checks if `Vy` `Nmatches` `Vx`
  `Nn`:          (not yet used)
  `No`(`Vx`):       `Norders` the letters in `Vx`
  `Np`(`Vx`, `Vy`):    `Npermutations` of the letters in `Vx`, excluding `Vy`
  `Nq`:          (not yet used)
  `Nr`(`Vx`, `Vy`):    `Nremoves` `Vy` from `Vx`
  `Ns`(`Vx`, `Vy`, `Vz`): `Nsubstitutes` `Vy` with `Vz` in`Vx`
  `Nt`(`Vx`):       makes `Ntext` version of `Vx`
  `Nu`(`Vx`):       `Nuppercases` `Vx`
  `Nv`:          (not yet used)
  `Nw`(`Vx`, `Vy`):    returns `Nwhich` of `Vy` matches `Vx`, or false (**)
  `Nx`:          (not yet used)
  `Ny`:          (not yet used)
  `Nz`(`Vx`):       does a naive `Nshift` of base64 text `Vx`
  `N$`:          (not yet used)
  `N_`:          (not yet used)

decorruption works by continuation-- if more data is needed, a function is
returned which takes in a string. the strings are lined up to remove corrupted
characters, and eventually the decorrupted string is returned instead of the
continuation function.

for the `Nwhich` function, the argument takes in a pair of regexps and values;
the value is returned when the regexp matches. this is useful for answering
a known list of questions.
